---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="about" description="About parrik — essays on signal-responsive systems across distributed systems, biology, and the practice.">
  <article class="about">

    <h1>About</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      parrik is a home for essays on a single shape.
      One failure mode surfacing across code, bodies, and the way we think.
      A memory structure that collapses corroboration.
      A cell that has lost tissue broadcast.
      A code change whose reviewer doesn't know what it touches.
      Different surfaces, same signal-loss. The writing attempts to name
      where it finds it.
    </p>

    <h2>Backstory</h2>

    <p>
      I grew up in India and came to the United States at 25 for AWS.
      The decade since has been distributed-systems engineering at a
      handful of companies — API Gateway, Cruise, Microsoft Azure,
      Bloomberg, Expedia — mostly as a Senior engineer, doing the
      work rather than chasing the title. Before that, heads-down IR
      and search-index work. Writing is the work right now, with
      the next thing still to be named.
    </p>

    <h2>Admirations</h2>

    <p>
      The writers I read hardest and whose work sets the bar:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Distributed systems</strong> — Martin Kleppmann,
        Marc Brooker, Kyle Kingsbury (Jepsen), Dan Luu, Hillel Wayne.
        Different registers; same discipline of not lying about what
        a system does under load.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Epistemics</strong> — Julia Galef, <em>The Scout
        Mindset</em>. The specific chapter that installs a habit is
        Ch. 6 "How Sure Are You?" — two hours of calibration exercises
        and the rest of her work lands differently.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Biology of context</strong> — Mina Bissell's "dynamic
        reciprocity" and Douglas Hanahan's successive hallmark papers
        (2000 / 2011 / 2022). The drift from cell-centric to
        ecosystem-centric cancer biology is the biological half of the
        through-line on this site.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Engineering-as-communication</strong> — Fred Brooks
        for the scaling law of shared context; Richard Hamming for
        problem selection; Patrick McKenzie for revenue-line honesty.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Practice</strong> — FKJ (French Kiwi Juice) as the
        sonic anchor. One person, many instruments, loop-based live
        craft, genre-fluid. The piano in the living room points at
        his shape.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Method</h2>

    <p>
      <em>Attribution is not confidence.</em> A claim repeated across
      five conversations is not five pieces of evidence — it is one
      derivation restated five times. Real confidence accumulates
      only from independent derivations: different episodes, different
      contexts, different evidence types. This is the load-bearing
      rule of the <a href="https://github.com/parrik/know-thyself">
      Know Thyself scaffold</a> and the background discipline of the
      essay shelf.
    </p>

    <h2>Currently</h2>

    <p>
      Writing the next essay, which names the through-line above
      explicitly. Reading DDIA Chapter 9. Practicing the piano.
      CrossFit daily. Library next door.
    </p>

    <h2>Elsewhere</h2>

    <p>
      <a href="https://github.com/parrik">github.com/parrik</a>
      &nbsp;·&nbsp;
      <a href="https://github.com/parrik/know-thyself">know-thyself scaffold (MIT)</a>
      &nbsp;·&nbsp;
      <a href="/rss.xml">RSS</a>
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>

